    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-10-18T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-10-18T06:00:00-05:00" n="126"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                <head>126. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Vietnam</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d126fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 851G.00A/10–1859. Secret; Limit Distribution. Repeated to Phnom Penh,
                        Bangkok, <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss> for <gloss
                            target="#t_POLAD1">POLAD</gloss>, and Vientiane.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1959-10-18T18:00:00+07:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 18, 1959—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1363. Ladejinsky leaving for US 18th. Expects arrive Washington about 25th. He
                    told me last night that in accordance my earlier suggestion he had brought up in
                    final interview with <persName corresp="#p_Diem1">Diem</persName> general
                    question <gloss target="#t_RKG1">RKG</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                    relations. Without mentioning our démarches, or radio, or dissidents <persName
                        corresp="#p_Diem1">Diem</persName> said Vice President had been right about
                    problem better <gloss target="#t_RKG1">RKG</gloss> relations. According
                        <persName corresp="#p_Diem1">Diem</persName> Vice President during and after
                        <persName corresp="#p_NSP1">Sihanouk</persName> visit had warned <persName
                        corresp="#p_Diem1">Diem</persName> not be taken in by <persName
                        corresp="#p_NSP1">Sihanouk</persName> promises of better relations and Vice
                    President had been proven correct since <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                    efforts better relations have not been successful.</p>
                <p>Following talk with Diem Ladejinsky asked his close friend the Vice President
                    about prospects better <gloss target="#t_RKG1">RKG</gloss> relations. Vice
                    President said nothing about untrustworthiness of <persName corresp="#p_NSP1"
                        >Sihanouk</persName>, but on contrary said it would be very easy to work out
                    arrangements to have better relations if it were not for anti-<gloss
                        target="#t_RKG1">RKG</gloss> activities and opposition of <persName
                        corresp="#p_Nhu1">Nhu</persName>. Ladejinsky convinced this is Vice
                    President’s sincere belief. I concur this evaluation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DE1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Durbrow</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
